value.value: A rare neurologic disorder caused by impingement of the nerve roots of the cauda equina secondary to disc herniation, spinal stenosis, vertebral fracture, neoplasm or infection. Clinical signs may include bladder or bowel dysfunction, paresthesia and weakness of the lower extremities. The clinical course rapidly deteriorates and necessitates emergent surgical decompression to minimize risk of incontinence, sexual dysfunction and permanent paralysis.
Evidence of non-familial idiopathic dystonia.
A malignant neoplasm that affects the glottic area of the larynx.  The vast majority of cases represent squamous cell carcinomas.
An acquired coagulation disorder characterized by the partial or complete absence of factor IX activity in the blood.
Sarcoidosis of the cerebrum.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic vascular disorder that affects the liver. Representative examples include veno-occlusive disease, hemangioma, lymphangioma, and angiosarcoma.
Inflammation of the glomeruli status post infection with nephritogenic streptococci, most often group A beta hemolytic streptococcus.

A histopathologic term for a pattern of diseases characterized by extensive crescent formation in the glomeruli; patients present clinically with rapid deterioration of renal function, and possible progression to end-stage renal failure within weeks or months.
A focal inflammation of glomeruli secondary to mesangial cell proliferation and matrix deposition within the mesangium.
Trauma to the bladder.
Necrotic changes in the bone tissue of the femoral head due to interruption of blood supply.
Liquid exudate from the eye.
A malignant neoplasm that affects the supraglottic area of the larynx.  The vast majority of cases are squamous cell carcinomas.
A finding which indicates an individual is not pregnant.

label.value: Electrocardiogram QRS Complex Shortened by ECG Finding

value.value: A QRS complex that is less than 120 milliseconds on electrocardiogram, reflexing rapid activation of the ventricles via the normal His-Purkinje system. It may indicate the presence of an arrhythmia originating above or within the His bundle.
A narrowing of the opening of the urethra at the external meatus.
Trauma to the lung bronchi.
Trauma to the thoracic diaphragm.
Trauma to the gallbladder.
Trauma to the colon.
A laboratory test result indicating a finding outside the parameters of normal urine measurements.
The psychological or physiological need to take a substance in order to experience its effects or to avoid the effects of its absence.
Damage to body tissue caused by exposure to a chemical substance.
A malignant neoplasm that affects the subglottic area of the larynx.  The vast majority of cases are squamous cell carcinomas.
A term that refers to the nature and/or clinical outcome of a disease (e.g., acute or chronic disease, aggressive or indolent disease, recurrent disease, etc.).
The left ventricular volume calculated as the difference between the epicardium delimited volume and the left ventricular chamber volume.
A proliferation of endometrial cells resulting in glandular enlargement and budding without changes in the basic structure of the endometrium. Epithelial atypia may be present or absent.

A rare variant of mycosis fungoides, characterized by the development of folds of lax skin in the axillae or groins.  It has been reported in association with Hodgkin lymphoma.  Morphologically, there is a dense granulomatous dermal atypical lymphocytic infiltrate, often associated with multinucleated giant cells.  Destruction of elastic tissue is present.  Most cases have an indolent clinical course.
Aplastic anemia caused by excessive absorption of radiation by the bone marrow.
Aplastic anemia caused by an infection.

A rare disorder which affects the volar surfaces of fingers. Clinical signs include recurrent, spontaneous or post-traumatic bruising of fingers. The clinical course of the resultant hematoma usually follows a pattern of resolution within days.
Accumulation of intraretinal fluid and protein in the macula, which may result in swelling and decreased central vision.

label.value: Anemia due to Disorder of Nucleotide Metabolism

value.value: A group of hemolytic anemias that result from either the deficiency or overproduction of several enzymes involved in metabolizing nucleotides.

A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm affecting the pleura.  A representative example of primary malignant pleural neoplasm is the malignant pleural mesothelioma.  A representative example of metastatic malignant neoplasm to the pleura is metastatic carcinoma that has spread to the pleura from another anatomic site.
A specific behavioral problem that occurs in persistent patterns and characteristic clusters and that causes clinically significant impairment.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of nucleated red cells in the peripheral blood.
Any form of anemia that results from the absence of, or the defective action of, any enzyme.

label.value: Acute Renal Failure with Renal Papillary Necrosis

value.value: Sudden and sustained deterioration of the kidney function with decreased glomerular filtration rate, and concommittant necrosis of the renal papillae; representative causes include sickle cell disease, heave analgesic use, diabetes mellitus, and pyelonephritis.
An infectious process that affects a tooth.  It is characterized by localized periapical or periodontal collection of pus.  It presents with pain and swelling of the gums and/or cheek.
Necrosis of bone due to an inadequate blood supply.
A benign vascular lesion characterized by the presence of a complex network of communicating arterial and venous vascular structures in the kidney.
A benign vascular lesion characterized by the presence of a complex network of communicating arterial and venous vascular structures in the retina.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the heart.
